1085–Female":"1085–Overleden","1090":"1090","about 1085":"circa 1085","1122":"1122","1144":"1144","1174":"1174","1085":"1085","about 1174":"circa 1174","Whittington Castle,Oswestry,Shropshire,England.":"Whittington, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Vengeons, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Vengeons, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Chirk, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom":"Chirk, Wrexham, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1085–":"about 1085–Deceased","1090–Male":"1090–Deceased","1122–Male":"1122–Deceased","1174–Male":"1174–Deceased","1085–Female":"1085–Deceased","1090":"1090","about 1085":"about 1085","1122":"1122","1144":"1144","1174":"1174","1085":"1085","about 1174":"about 1174","Whittington Castle,Oswestry,Shropshire,England.":"Whittington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Vengeons, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Vengeons, Manche, Lower Normandy, France","Chirk, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom":"Chirk, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Metz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i>, composed of ancient Germanic <i>maht</i> ‘might, strength’ + <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from Metz in Lorraine, which took its name from a Gaulish tribe, the <i>Mediomatrici</i>; in the name of the place this became abbreviated to <i>Mettis</i>, hence the modern name.","German: from <i>Mätz</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mette","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz  ).","North German: occupational name for a miller, from Middle Low German <i>matte</i>, <i>mette</i> ‘dry measure’.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>mete</i> ‘boundary stone, boundary’ (from Latin <i>meta</i> ‘bounded estate’)."]},{"name":"Metzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Metz (see   Metz  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a bricklayer, Middle Dutch <i>metsere</i>."]},{"name":"Metts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Metz  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Metze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Gerhard, Gernot.","German:","metronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz   1)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William de Metz was born about 1085, in Vengeons, Manche, Lower Normandy, France. She had at least 2 sons with Gronwy ap Tudur. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1085–":"umbes 1085–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1122–Male":"1122–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1085–Female":"1085–Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1085":"umbes 1085","1122":"1122","1144":"1144","1174":"1174","1085":"1085","about 1174":"umbes 1174","Whittington Castle,Oswestry,Shropshire,England.":"Whittington, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Vengeons, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Vengeons, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Chir